<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_dictionary` row that
    declares the `priority` Choice field on the `x_[scope]_case` custom table
    inside the scoped application `x_[scope]_case_management`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field      Type      Constraints
        priority   Choice    Low, Medium, High, Critical

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning):
        choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml -> Low, Medium, High, Critical
        and the assigned-folder description establishes that new cases default
        to `Medium` priority.

    This dictionary entry ONLY declares that the `priority` Choice field exists
    on the parent table. The choice values themselves (Low, Medium, High,
    Critical) are authored as separate sys_choice records in
    ../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml. This separation is a deliberate
    consequence of the ServiceNow Choice-field design pattern: a sys_dictionary
    row declares the column shape; sibling sys_choice rows declare the allowed
    string-label values keyed by `name` + `element` lookup against this entry.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 178-179:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_priority")
            private String priority;
        ArkCase's `priority` was a free-form String column on the
        `acm_case_file` JPA entity - any caller could write any string and
        the JPA layer enforced no enumeration. The ServiceNow target
        constrains the field to a controlled vocabulary of four labels
        through the `<choice>3</choice>` setting plus the sibling
        sys_choice records. This prevents typos, enables consistent
        Manager View dashboard analytics, and keeps the priority
        semantics deterministic across internal forms, the Table API,
        the scripted REST submission endpoint, and seed scripts.
      - The field name is `priority` (lowercase, 8 chars; NOT `casePriority`,
        NOT `case_priority`) per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim. This matches
        the conventional ServiceNow Choice-field naming convention across
        the platform (incident.priority, sc_request.priority,
        change_request.priority).

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: `<name>` resolves to `x_[scope]_case`
        within the scoped application, and `<sys_scope>` / `<sys_package>`
        bind THIS dictionary record to the same scope by `source` attribute
        lookup. NO global-scope writes - the OOB tables `task`, `incident`,
        `sys_user`, etc. are never modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]_case_management`), not by literal sys_id. The `<sys_id>`
        text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of the canonical field identifier `x_[scope]_case.priority`)
        and is NOT a reference to any other record. The deterministic
        derivation makes the Update Set re-importable on a fresh PDI
        without sys_id collisions: re-importing the same XML on the same
        or any future PDI resolves the same sys_id and idempotently
        updates the same dictionary row rather than creating a duplicate.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP convention;
        the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App Engine Studio
        creation time.
      - mandatory=true at the dictionary level (AAP Section 0.4.1: every
        case has a priority because the Manager View "All cases by
        priority" bar chart per ../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_priority
        .xml would otherwise contain a meaningless "(none)" bucket that
        skewed analytics; AAP Section 0.7.1 also establishes that the
        full role x CRUD matrix presupposes complete categorical
        attribution on every case row). With `default_value=Medium` the
        mandatory constraint is always satisfiable on insert without a
        user prompt; the Choice can still be re-set to Low / High /
        Critical by the case_manager or assigned case_agent through the
        standard form before save.
      - read_only=false: an internal user (case_manager or assigned
        case_agent within the AAP Section 0.5.6 "Assigned only" condition)
        editing the case record may re-prioritize a case as new
        information emerges (e.g., a Low priority complaint that
        escalates to Critical). The read_only=false setting permits the
        write through the standard form, the Table API, and the seed
        scripts; the Experience Portal lookup page does NOT expose this
        field per AAP Section 0.7.4 ("the lookup page returns ONLY
        status, subject, opened_date - no internal fields exposed").
      - default_value=Medium: explicit Title Case per the agent prompt's
        Phase 4 verbatim. The PDI's auto-numbered case-number generator
        (CASE0000001 format from ../numbers/sys_number_x_[scope]_case
        .xml) plus this default value together let a portal-originated
        anonymous submission complete the entire mandatory field set
        (subject, type, description, requester_name, requester_email,
        priority, status) using the user-supplied free-text inputs from
        AAP Section 0.4.4 PLUS server-side defaults for the categorical
        and lifecycle fields - WITHOUT exposing priority on the public
        portal page (per AAP Section 0.7.4 minimal exposure principle).
        The scripted REST endpoint
        ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
        therefore does NOT need to set this field explicitly; the
        platform applies the default at insert time.
      - audit=false: the field tracks a categorical attribute, not a
        regulated lifecycle identifier. Per AAP Section 0.7.2 this POC
        is scoped to functional capability, not full audit-trail
        compliance. The `status` field in this same scoped table
        (../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_status.xml) IS audited because
        every state transition (Draft -> Open -> In Progress -> ...)
        must be reconstructable for forensic correctness; priority,
        being a re-prioritization rather than a regulated lifecycle
        event, does not require that level of historical fidelity for
        the POC scope.
      - max_length 40 is sufficient for the longest defined label
        "Critical" (8 chars) with substantial headroom for future
        extensible labels (e.g., "Severe", "Emergency") - though AAP
        Section 0.5.7's enumeration is the authoritative four-value
        set for the POC.
      - choice 3 = "Choice list, no description column" - the standard
        Choice-field configuration when a sibling sys_choice record set
        defines the allowed values without a long-form description
        column on the dropdown.
      - No reference target: this is a String-backed Choice field, not
        a Reference field. All `<reference*>` elements are empty and
        `<table_reference>false</table_reference>`.
      - text_index=false: priority is a low-cardinality enumerated
        Choice (four values), so full-text indexing would be wasteful.
        The platform's standard list/report/dashboard surface filters
        on the column directly via GlideRecord addQuery without needing
        a full-text index.
      - No PII: the field stores only categorical urgency labels chosen
        from a controlled vocabulary; no real names, email addresses, or
        organizational identifiers are derived from or stored in this
        column.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      - This record MUST load AFTER `../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml`
        (parent table), since `<name>x_[scope]_case</name>` references
        the table by name.
      - This record MUST load BEFORE the consumers that read or write
        the `priority` column:
          * ../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml (the choice values
            Low, Medium, High, Critical - which reference this
            dictionary entry by `name` + `element` lookup; the choice
            ORDER drives dropdown UX from least-to-most urgent)
          * ../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_priority.xml (Manager
            View bar chart grouped by this field per AAP Section 0.4.1)
          * ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_*.xml (synthetic
            demo cases that populate this field across the four
            priority values to exercise the Manager View bar chart
            and demonstrate the Choice-field behavior on the
            internal form)
-->
<record_update table="sys_dictionary">
    <sys_dictionary action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <array>false</array>
        <attributes/>
        <audit>false</audit>
        <calculation/>
        <choice>3</choice>
        <choice_field/>
        <choice_table/>
        <column_label>Priority</column_label>
        <comments>Mandatory Choice categorizing case urgency. Values: Low, Medium, High, Critical. Default: Medium. Used by ../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_priority.xml (Manager View dashboard bar chart). Replaces ArkCase CaseFile.priority (free-form String).</comments>
        <create_roles/>
        <default_value>Medium</default_value>
        <defaultsort/>
        <delete_roles/>
        <dependent/>
        <dependent_on_field/>
        <display>true</display>
        <dynamic_creation>false</dynamic_creation>
        <dynamic_creation_script/>
        <dynamic_default_value/>
        <dynamic_ref_qual/>
        <element>priority</element>
        <element_reference>false</element_reference>
        <foreign_database/>
        <function_definition/>
        <function_field>false</function_field>
        <internal_type>string</internal_type>
        <mandatory>true</mandatory>
        <max_length>40</max_length>
        <name>x_[scope]_case</name>
        <next_element/>
        <primary>false</primary>
        <read_only>false</read_only>
        <read_roles/>
        <reference/>
        <reference_cascade_rule/>
        <reference_floor/>
        <reference_key/>
        <reference_qual/>
        <reference_qual_condition/>
        <reference_type/>
        <sizeclass/>
        <spell_check>false</spell_check>
        <staged>false</staged>
        <sys_class_name>sys_dictionary</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>7584a06a06745f24e42efb27f0ae5975</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name/>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]_case_management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_dictionary_x_[scope]_case_priority</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <table_reference>false</table_reference>
